Processing is a free open source development environment that allows users to experiment with computer graphics using Java. Its a good tool for teaching general programming techniques using a visual medium. See <a href="https://processing.org/">processing.org/</a><br/><br/>One of the many things you can do with processing is draw fractals.<br/>The term <strong><em>fractal</em></strong> (from the Latin <em>fractus</em>, meaning “broken”) was coined by the mathematician Benoit Mandelbrot in 1975. In his seminal work “The Fractal Geometry of Nature,” he defines a fractal as “a rough or fragmented geometric shape that can be split into parts, each of which is (at least approximately) a reduced-size copy of the whole.”<br/><br/><img alt="" src="/posts/files/73a29012-4058-4319-bd6c-bea9781d2b38.png"/><br/><br/>Using recursion in processing, we can create complex fractals like the one above using relatively few lines of code.<br/><br/><span>Recursion can be defined as:<br/> Relating to or involving a program or routine of which a part requires the application of the whole, so that its explicit interpretation requires in general many successive executions.</span><br/><br/>Or in basic terms it's a method that calls itself until an exit condition is met. <br/>Here's a basic example:<br/><pre class="code">void setup() {
  size(640, 360);
  drawCircle(320,160,700);
}

void drawCircle(int x, int y, float radius) {
  ellipse(x, y, radius, radius);
  //Every recursive function needs an exit condition, or youll be drawing circles forever!
  //Here ours will terminate when the radius in smaller than 2 pixels 
  if(radius &gt; 2) {
    radius *= 0.75f;

    drawCircle(x, y, radius);
  }
}<br/></pre>This simple program will draw a circle in the middle of the screen, sets the radius to 0.75% of what it is currently and then re draws the circle until the radius gets to small. This results in: <br/><img alt="" src="/posts/files/8981e145-f319-4b8e-a00d-199ce7c2b93c.png"/><br/><br/>
